[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] Later in 1899, ACF acquired the Bloomsburg Car Manufacturing Company of Bloomsburg, Pennsylvania.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] Orders for new freight cars were made very quickly, with several hundred cars ordered in the first year alone.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] Two years later, ACF acquired the Jackson and Sharp Company (founded 1863 in Wilmington, Delaware) and the Common Sense Bolster Company (of Chicago, Illinois).
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] The unified company made a large investment in the former Jackson & Woodin plant in Pennsylvania, spending about $3 million.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] It was at this plant that ACF built the first all-steel passenger car in the world in 1904.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] The car was built for the Interborough Rapid Transit system of New York City, the first of 300 such cars ordered by that system.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] In 1903, the company was operating overseas in Trafford Park, Manchester, England, and it was featured on a Triumphal Arch built for the Royal Visit of Edward VII and Queen Alexandra in 1903.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] The factory buildings were later used by Ford cars, which began manufacturing at Trafford Park in 1911.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] 1904 and 1905 saw ACF build several motor cars and trailers for the London Underground.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] In those two years, ACF also acquired the Southern Car and Foundry (founded 1899 in Memphis, Tennessee), Indianapolis Car and Foundry, and Indianapolis Car Company.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] Woodin, formerly president of Jackson and Woodin Manufacturing Company, was promoted to become president of ACF.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] Woodin would later become Secretary of the Treasury under U.S.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] During World War I, ACF produced artillery gun mounts and ammunition, submarine chasers and other boats, railway cars, and other equipment to support the Allies.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] ACF ranked 36th among United States corporations in the value of World War II production contracts.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] In World War 2, ACF produced tanks and bulldozers for the military.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] The Berwick plant constructed over 15,000 tanks between 1940 and 1944.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] In the past, ACF built passenger and freight cars, including covered hopper cars for hauling such cargo as corn and other grains.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] One of the largest customers was the Union Pacific Railroad, whose armour-yellow carbon-steel lightweight passenger rolling stock was mostly built by ACF.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] The famous dome-observation car "Native Son" was an ACF product.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] Another important ACF railroad production were the passenger cars of the Missouri River "Eagle", a Missouri Pacific streamliner put in service in March 1940.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] This train, in its original shape, consisted of six cars including one baggage, one baggage-mail, two coaches one food and beverage car and finally the observation lounge-parlor car.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] All the passenger equipment was styled by industrial designer Raymond Loewy.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] Today, the U.S. passenger car market is erratic in production and is mostly handled by specialty manufacturers and foreign corporations.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] Competitors Budd, Pullman-Standard, Rohr Industries, and the St.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] Louis Car Company have all either left the market or gone out of business.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] The manufacturing facility in Milton, Pennsylvania, was served by the Norfolk Southern Railway and was capable of manufacturing railcars and all related railcar components.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] The plant was capable of producing pressure vessels in sizes 18,000–61,000 gwc, including propane tanks, compressed gas storage, LPG storage, and all related components, including heads.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] The plant, covering 48 acres, provided 500,000 square feet of covered work area and seven miles of storage tracks.
[src:carter-carburetor/american-car-and-foundry-company] The Huntington, West Virginia, production site ceased production in late 2009, and was demolished in 2021.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A **carburetor** (also spelled **carburettor** or **carburetter**) is a device used by a gasoline internal combustion engine to control and mix air and fuel entering the engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The primary method of adding fuel to the intake air is through the Venturi effect or Bernoulli's principle or with a pitot tube in the main metering circuit, though various other components are also used to provide extra fuel or air in specific circumstances.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Since the 1990s, carburetors have been largely replaced by fuel injection for cars and trucks, but carburetors are still used by some small engines (e.g. lawnmowers, generators, and concrete mixers) and motorcycles.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In addition, they are still widely used on piston-engine–driven aircraft.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Diesel engines have always used fuel injection instead of carburetors, as they do not compress an air-fuel mix and instead require fuel injection much later in the compression stroke.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The term "carburetor" is derived from the English verb *carburet*, meaning "to charge with hydrocarbons"; in early motoring books the product of the carburetor is *carburetted air*, i.e. air charged with hydrocarbon vapour.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] This meaning superseded that from the late eighteenth century in which *carburet* was a noun for which we now use the word *carbide*.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A carburetor charges the intake air with vapour from a hydrocarbon-based fuel, such as petrol or autogas.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The name is spelled "carburetor" in American English and "carburettor" in British English.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Colloquial abbreviations include "carb" in the UK and North America or "carby" in Australia.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Air from the atmosphere enters the carburetor (usually via an air cleaner), has fuel added within the carburetor, then the air fuel mixture leaves the carburetor and enters the inlet manifold, then through the inlet valve(s), and finally into the combustion chamber.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Most engines use a single carburetor shared among all of the cylinders, though some high-performance engines historically had multiple carburetors and/or throats.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] If the tube is a constant diameter the configuration is slightly simpler than in the cross-section diagram shown above right.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In most cases (except for the *accelerator pump*), the driver pressing the throttle pedal does not directly increase the fuel entering the engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Instead, the airflow through the carburetor increases, which in turn increases the amount of fuel drawn into the intake mixture.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a reduction of area along the air flow rather than from ambient pressure to the fuel entry point the effect can be described as the Venturi effect, but that is still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a dynamic pressure (facing the incoming air) within the air entry point rather than from ambient pressure instead the carbureter can be described as the Pitot tube type, but that is also still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The actual fuel and air flows are more complicated and need correction.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] This might be done variously at lower speeds or higher speeds, or over the whole range by a variable emulsion device to add air to the fuel after the main jets/s.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Zenith-Stromberg) variable jet carburetors, it was mainly controlled by varying the jet size.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The orientation of the carburetor is a key design consideration.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Older engines used **updraft** carburetors, where the air enters from below the carburetor and exits through the top.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] From the late 1930s, **downdraft** carburetors become more commonly used (especially in the United States), along with **side draft** carburetors (especially in Europe).
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The main metering circuit usually consists of barrel/s which reduces to a narrow part where the air is at its highest speed, forming a choke or venturi.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Fuel is usually introduced into the air stream at that narrow part through small tubes leading from the main jet.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The change in area is only necessary for a Venturi carburetor but in other configurations the barrel/s can be of constant area with the fuel entry anywhere along it.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Downstream of a choke or venturi is a throttle (usually in the form of a butterfly valve) which is used to control the amount of air entering the carburetor.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In a car, this throttle is usually mechanically connected to the vehicle's throttle pedal, which varies engine speed.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] At lesser throttle openings, the air speed may be insufficient to maintain the main fuel flow, so then the fuel may be supplied by the carburetor's idle and off-idle circuits usually near the narrow gap between the edge of the butterfly plate and the body to give sufficient local air speed.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] At greater throttle openings, the speed of air increases, which lowers the pressure of the air and draws more fuel into the airstream.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] At the same time, the reduced manifold vacuum results in less fuel flow through the idle and off-idle circuits.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] During cold weather fuel vaporizes less readily and tends to condense on the walls of the intake manifold, starving the cylinders of fuel and making cold starts difficult.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Additional fuel is required (for a given amount of air) to start and run the engine until it warms up, provided by a *choke valve*.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] While the engine is warming up the choke valve is partially closed, restricting the flow of air at the entrance to the carburetor.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] This increases the vacuum in the main metering circuit, causing more fuel to be supplied to the engine via the main jets.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Prior to the late 1950s the choke was manually operated by the driver, often using a lever or knob on the dashboard.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Since then, automatic chokes became more commonplace.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] These either use a bimetallic thermostat to automatically regulate the choke based on the temperature of the engine's coolant liquid, an electrical resistance heater to do so, or air drawn through a tube connected to an engine exhaust source.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A choke left closed after the engine has warmed up increases the engine's fuel consumption and exhaust gas emissions, and causes the engine to run rough and lack power due to an over-rich fuel mixture.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] However, excessive fuel can flood an engine and prevent it from starting.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] To remove the excess fuel, many carburetors with automatic chokes allow it to be held open (by manually, depressing the accelerator pedal to the floor and briefly holding it there while cranking the starter) to allow extra air into the engine until the excess fuel is cleared out.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Another method used by carburetors to improve the operation of a cold engine is a *fast idle cam*, which is connected to the choke and prevents the throttle from closing fully while the choke is in operation.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The resulting increase in idle speed provides a more stable idle for a cold engine (by better atomizing the cold fuel) and helps the engine warm up quicker.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The system within a carburetor that meters fuel when the engine is running at low RPM.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The idle circuit is generally activated by vacuum near the (near closed) throttle plate, where the air speed increases to cause a low-pressure area in the idle passage/port, thus causing fuel to flow through the idle jet.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The idle jet is set at some constant value by the carburetor manufacturer, thus flowing a specified amount of fuel.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Many carburetors use an off-idle circuit, which includes an additional fuel jet which is briefly used as the throttle starts to open.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] This jet is located in a low-pressure area caused by the high air speed near the (partly closed) throttle.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The additional fuel it provides is used to compensate for the reduced vacuum that occurs when the throttle is opened, thus smoothing the transition from the idle circuit to the main metering circuit.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In a four-stroke engine it is often desirable to provide extra fuel to the engine at high loads (to increase the power output and reduce engine knocking).
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A 'power valve', which is a spring-loaded valve in the carburetor that is held shut by engine vacuum, is often used to do so.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] As the airflow through the carburetor increases, the reduced manifold vacuum pulls the power valve open, allowing more fuel into the main metering circuit.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In a two-stroke engine, the carburetor power valve operates in the opposite manner: in most circumstances the valve allows extra fuel into the engine, then at a certain engine RPM it closes to reduce the fuel entering the engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] This is done in order to extend the engine's maximum RPM, since many two-stroke engines can temporarily achieve higher RPM with a leaner air-fuel ratio.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] This is not to be confused with the unrelated exhaust power valve arrangements used on two-stroke engines.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A metering rod or step-up rod system is sometimes used as an alternative to a power valve in a four-stroke engine in order to supply extra fuel at high loads.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] One end of the rods is tapered, which sits in the main metering jets and acts as a valve for fuel flow in the jets.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] At high engine loads, the rods are lifted away from the jets (either mechanically or using manifold vacuum), increasing the volume of fuel flow through the jet.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] These systems have been used by the Rochester Quadrajet and in the 1950s Carter carburetors.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] While the main metering circuit can adequately supply fuel to the engine in steady-state conditions, the inertia of fuel (being higher than that of air) causes a temporary shortfall as the throttle is opened.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Therefore, an accelerator pump is often used to briefly provide extra fuel as the throttle is opened.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] When the driver presses the throttle pedal, a small piston or diaphragm pump injects extra fuel directly into the carburetor throat.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The accelerator pump can also be used to "prime" an engine with extra fuel prior to attempting a cold start.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In order to ensure an adequate supply at all times, carburetors include a reservoir of fuel, called a "float chamber" or "float bowl".
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Fuel is delivered to the float chamber by a fuel pump or by gravity with the fuel tank located higher than the carburetor.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A floating inlet valve regulates the fuel entering the float chamber, assuring a constant level.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In some small engines that may instead of a float chamber just use a fuel tank close below the carburetor and use the fuel suction to supply the fuel.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Unlike in a fuel injected engine, the fuel system in a carbureted engine is not pressurized.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] For engines where the intake air travelling through the carburetor is pressurized (such as where the carburetor is downstream of a supercharger) the entire carburetor must be contained in an airtight pressurized box to operate.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] However, this is not necessary where the carburetor is upstream of the supercharger.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Problems of fuel boiling and vapor lock can occur in carbureted engines, especially in hotter climates.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Since the float chamber is located close to the engine, heat from the engine (including for several hours after the engine is shut off) can cause the fuel to heat up to the point of vaporization.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] This causes air bubbles in the fuel (similar to the air bubbles that necessitate brake bleeding), which prevents the flow of fuel and is known as 'vapor lock'.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] If an engine must be operated when the carburetor is not in an upright orientation (for example in a chainsaw or airplane), a float chamber and gravity activated float valve would not be suitable.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Instead, a diaphragm chamber is typically used.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] This consists of a flexible diaphragm on one side of the fuel chamber, connected to a needle valve which regulates the fuel entering the chamber.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber (controlled by the throttling valve/butterfly valve) decreases, the diaphragm moves inward (downward), which closes the needle valve to admit less fuel.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber increases, the diaphragm moves outward (upward) which opens the needle valve to admit more fuel, allowing the engine to generate more power.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A balanced state is reached which creates a steady fuel reservoir level, that remains constant in any orientation.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The basic design for a carburetor consists of a single venturi (main metering circuit), though designs with two or four venturi (two-barrel and four-barrel carburetors respectively) are also quite commonplace.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Typically the barrels consist of "primary" barrel(s) used for lower load situations and secondary barrel(s) activating when required to provide additional air/fuel at higher loads.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The primary and secondary venturi are often sized differently and incorporate different features to suit the situations in which they are used.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Many four-barrel carburetors use two primary and two secondary barrels.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A four-barrel design of two primary and two secondary barrels was commonly used in V8 engines to conserve fuel at low engine speeds while still affording an adequate supply at high.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The use of multiple carburetors (e.g., a carburetor for each cylinder or pair of cylinders) also results in the intake air being drawn through multiple venturi.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Some high-performance engines have used multiple two-barrel or four-barrel carburetors, for example six two-barrel carburetors on Ferrari V12s.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In 1826, American engineer Samuel Morey received a patent for a "gas or vapor engine", which had a carburetor that mixed turpentine and air.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In 1888/1889 German engineer Siegfried Marcus produced a car powered by a petrol engine (which also debuted the first magneto ignition system).
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Karl Benz introduced his single-cylinder four-stroke powered Benz Patent-Motorwagen in 1885.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] All three of these engines used surface carburetors, which operated by moving air across the top of a vessel containing the fuel.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The first float-fed carburetor design, which used an atomizer nozzle, was introduced by German engineers Wilhelm Maybach and Gottlieb Daimler in their 1885 *Grandfather Clock engine*.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The Butler Petrol Cycle car—built in England in 1888—also used a float-fed carburetor.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In 1892 Maybach produced an important carburetor with a jet spraying into a venturi, as would become the norm; this was patented in 1893.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The first carburetor for a stationary engine was patented in 1893 by Hungarian engineers János Csonka and Donát Bánki.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The first four-barrel carburetors were the Carter Carburetor WCFB and the identical Rochester 4GC, introduced in various General Motors models for 1952.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Oldsmobile referred the new carburetor as the "Quadri-Jet" (original spelling) while Buick called it the "Airpower".
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In the United States, carburetors were the common method of fuel delivery for most US-made gasoline (petrol) engines until the late 1980s, when fuel injection became the preferred method.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] One of the last motorsport users of carburetors was NASCAR, which switched to electronic fuel injection after the 2011 Sprint Cup series.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] NASCAR still uses the four-barrel carburetor in the NASCAR Xfinity Series.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] In Europe, carburetors were largely replaced by fuel injection in the late 1980s, although fuel injection had been increasingly used in luxury cars and sports cars since the 1970s.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] EEC legislation required all vehicles sold and produced in member countries to have a catalytic converter after December 1992.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] This legislation had been in the pipeline for some time, with many cars becoming available with catalytic converters or fuel injection from around 1990.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A significant concern for aircraft engines is the formation of ice inside the carburetor.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The temperature of air within the carburetor can be reduced by up to 40 °C (72 °F), due to a combination of the reduced air pressure in the venturi and the latent heat of the evaporating fuel.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The conditions during the descent to landing are particularly conducive to icing, since the engine is run at idle for a prolonged period with the throttle closed.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Icing can also occur in cruise conditions at altitude.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A carburetor heat system is often used to prevent icing.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] This system consists of a secondary air intake which passes around the exhaust, in order to heat the air before it enters the carburetor.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Typically, the system is operated by the pilot manually switching the intake air to travel via the heated intake path as required.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] The carburetor heat system reduces the power output (due to the lower density of heated air) and causes the intake air filter to be bypassed, therefore the system is only used when there is a risk of icing.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] If the engine is operating at idle RPM, another method to prevent icing is to periodically open the throttle, which increases the air temperature within the carburetor.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Carburetor icing also occurs on other applications and various methods have been employed to solve this problem.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] On inline engines the intake and exhaust manifolds are on the same side of the head.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Heat from the exhaust is used to warm the intake manifold and in turn the carburetor.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] On V configurations, exhaust gases were directed from one head through the intake cross over to the other head.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] One method for regulating the exhaust flow on the cross over for intake warming was a weighted eccentric butterfly valve called a heat riser that remained closed at idle and opened at higher exhaust flow.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] Some vehicles used a heat stove around the exhaust manifold.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] It was connected to the air filter intake via tubing and supplied warmed air to the air filter.
[src:carter-carburetor/carburetor] A vacuum controlled butterfly valve pre heat tube on the intake horn of the air cleaner would open allowing cooler air when engine load increased.
[src:carter-carburetor/carl-breer] He was born on November 8, 1883, in Los Angeles, California.
[src:carter-carburetor/carl-breer] He was married to the sister of Frederick Morrell Zeder and had four sons.
[src:carter-carburetor/carl-breer] He attended the Los Angeles Commercial High School.
[src:carter-carburetor/carl-breer] He completed his degree in mechanical engineering.
[src:carter-carburetor/carl-breer] He was one of the Studebaker engineers known as the Three Musketeers.
[src:carter-carburetor/carl-breer] They were instrumental in the founding of the Chrysler Corporation, and were hand-picked by Walter Chrysler to come with him when he started the new company.
[src:carter-carburetor/carl-breer] He was inducted into the Automotive Hall of Fame in 1976.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] The **Carter Carburetor Company** was an American manufacturer of carburetors, primarily for the automobile industry.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] Louis, Missouri, in 1909 and ceased operation in 1985.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] Founder William Carter started experimenting with automotive carburetors while running a successful bicycle shop.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] His first, a cast brass model, could meter and deliver fuel more accurately than many competing units.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] He sold Carter Carburetor Company 13 years after founding it to American Car and Foundry Company.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] Carl Breer wrote that, upon learning that the Ball family (owners of Ball & Ball) was planning to leave the carburetor business, he set them up with Carter, which continued to produce the Ball & Ball basic designs used by Chrysler.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] Carter adapted carburetors for Willys Jeep four-cylinder engines, waterproofing them for water crossings and making it possible to keep the engine going even on a steep incline (the YS carburetor).
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] Carter also produced the first American four-barrel carburetor, used for Buick’s 1952 straight-eight, and followed by the William Carter Four-Barrel (WCFB) on the 1955 Chrysler C300.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] This was eventually superseded by the Aluminum Four-Barrel (AFB) and Air Valve Secondaries (AVS) models.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] The final Chrysler use of four-barrel Carter carburetors was the Thermo-Quad, which used a lightweight thermoplastic float bowl, on the most powerful Chrysler engines.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] Carter produced Rochester Quadrajet carburetors for their rival maker whenever demand outpaced Rochester's ability to make them.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] They were identical to Rochester's units, except the Carter name was stamped into the body.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] In Carter's final years in the early 1980s, they also produced Weber carburetors under license, such as the three-barrel Type 40IDA sold as replacements (or fuel injection retrofits) for 1960s and 1970s Porsche 911 S.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] In 1984, with fuel injection having replaced carburetors on most cars, the plant closed.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] In 1985, American Car and Foundry shut down the entire Carter Carburetor foundry, a year later ceding the PCB-contaminated property to the City of St.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] The site contains contaminants including TCE and PCBs that penetrate the topsoil to bedrock.
[src:carter-carburetor/carter-carburetor] In 2013, cleanup was estimated to cost US$30 million.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The **LA engine** is a family of overhead-valve small-block 90° V-configured gasoline engines built by Chrysler Corporation between 1964 and 2003.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Primarily V8s, the line includes a single V6 and V10, both derivations of its Magnum series introduced in 1992.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] A replacement of the Chrysler A engine, they were factory-installed in passenger vehicles, trucks and vans, commercial vehicles, marine and industrial applications.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Their combustion chambers are wedge-shaped, rather than polyspheric, as in the A engine, or hemispheric in the Chrysler Hemi.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] LA engines have the same 4.46 in (113 mm) bore spacing as the A engines.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] LA engines were made at Chrysler's Mound Road Engine plant in Detroit, Michigan, as well as plants in Canada and Mexico.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The "LA" stands for "Light A," as the 1956–1967 "A" engine it was closely based on and shares many parts with was nearly 50 pounds heavier.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The "LA" and "A" production overlapped from 1964–1966 in the U.S. and through 1967 in export vehicles when the "A" 318 engine was phased out.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The basic design of the LA engine would go unchanged through the development of the "Magnum" upgrade (1992–1993), and continue into the 2000s with changes to enhance power and efficiency.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 238.2 cu in (3.9 L) V6 was introduced with the Dodge Dakota for 1987, and replaced the older, longer Slant-Six in the Dodge Ram trucks and vans for 1988.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] It is essentially a six-cylinder version of the 318 V8.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The bore and stroke are 99.3 mm (3.9 in) and 84 mm (3.3 in), respectively.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Output was 125 hp (93 kW) and 195 lb⋅ft (264 N⋅m) until it was replaced by the 3.9 L Magnum starting in 1992.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In 1987, it used a two-barrel Holley carburetor and hydraulic valve lifters.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In 1988, it was upgraded with throttle-body fuel injection and roller lifters.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] For the 1992 Magnum update, the throttle-body fuel injection was upgraded to a multi-port fuel injection system.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In 1997, it was then upgraded to sequential fuel injection.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The engine was produced through 2003 before it was replaced with the 3.7 L PowerTech V6.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 273 cu in (4.5 L) was the first LA engine, beginning model year 1964 and offered through 1969, rated at 180 hp (134 kW).
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] It had a mechanical solid lifter valvetrain until 1968 when hydraulic lifters were introduced; hydraulic lifters generally make for a quieter valvetrain.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The reciprocating assembly included a cast or forged steel crankshaft, drop forged steel connecting rods and cast aluminum pistons.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The valvetrain consisted of a cast nodular iron camshaft, solid or hydraulic lifters, solid pushrods, and shaft-mounted, malleable iron rocker arms (stamped steel on later hydraulic-cam engines).
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] These actuated the overhead steel intake and exhaust valves.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The cylinder heads featured wedge-shaped combustion chambers with a single intake and a single exhaust valve for each cylinder.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Spark plugs were located in the side of the cylinder head, between the exhaust ports.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] A high-performance 235 hp (175 kW) was offered from 1965 to 1967; called the "Commando", it was standard in the Barracuda Formula S model and optional in all other compact models excluding station wagons.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] It featured a 4-barrel carburetor and matching intake manifold, chrome unsilenced air cleaner with callout sticker, longer-duration and higher-lift camshaft and stronger valve springs, 10.5:1 compression ratio, and special black wrinkle valve covers with extruded aluminum appliqués.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] It was fitted to a low-restriction exhaust system with a 2.5 in (64 mm) exhaust pipe, collector-type Y-junction, and exposed resonator.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] For 1965 (only), the muffler was of "straight through" construction.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] A special version, exclusive to the 1966 Dodge Dart, was available.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] It used a 0.5 in (12.7 mm) lift solid-lifter camshaft, fabricated-steel-tube exhaust, and a Holley 4-barrel carburetor, producing 275 hp (205 kW) (1 hp/cu in).
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The car so equipped was called the "D-Dart," a reference to its classification in NHRA D-stock for drag racing, which was the car's only intended purpose.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] It appeared in volume production beginning with the 1968 model year, replacing the last of the export "A" 318 engines equipped with polyspherical chambered heads ("A" 318 engines were not offered in 1967 domestic vehicles).
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The LA engine was available until 1991, when it was superseded by the Magnum version.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] It used hydraulic lifters and a two-barrel carburetor for most of its production, though four-barrel Carter Thermo-Quad and Rochester Quadrajet carburetors were used in police applications starting in 1978 and 1985, respectively.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 318 two-barrel ELD received roller lifters and a fast-burn chambered cylinder head in 1985 (the four-barrel police ELE 318 continued to use modified J heads and hydraulic flat valve lifters through 1989).
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Throttle-body electronic fuel injection was factory equipment on the 1981–1983 Imperial.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] From 1988 to 1991, another throttle-body fuel injection system was used for truck and van applications.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In the mid-1960s, Chrysler decided to adapt the 318 cu in (5.2 L) small block V8 into a lightweight, high output engine equally suited for drag strip or street performance use.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Its block was bored out to 4.04 in (102.6 mm) but its 3.31 in (84.1 mm) stroke left unchanged, resulting in the 340 cu in (5.6 L) engine introduced for the 1968 model year.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Anticipating higher loads resulting from racing operation, the engineers fitted a forged shot peened steel crankshaft instead of the cast steel unit used in the 318.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] This also included shot peened hammer-forged steel connecting rods and high compression cast aluminum pistons with full floating pins.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] A 4-barrel carburetor was mated to a high-rise, dual plane intake manifold feeding high-flow cylinder heads that are still considered among the best of that era.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Its big ports used 2.02 in (51 mm) intake and 1.60 in (41 mm) exhaust valves.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] An aggressive cam was fitted to take advantage of the much better breathing top end.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 1968 4-speed cars got an even hotter cam, but it was discontinued for 1969, where both automatic and manual cars shared the same cam.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The engine was equipped with hydraulic lifters and two bolt main bearing caps, leading some to initially underestimate the 340's potential.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 1968–71 340's compression ratio was 10.5:1, placing it near the limit of what was possible on pump gasoline during that era.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 340 also used additional heavy-duty parts, such as a double-row roller timing chain and sump-mounted windage tray.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Power output was officially stated as 275 hp (205 kW) gross for the 4 barrel.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In 1970, Chrysler introduced a special triple carburetor version of the 340 with triple 2-barrels at 290 hp (216 kW) gross.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Exclusively called the catchy **Six-Pack** on the Trans-Am targeted Dodge Challenger TA models, the same configuration was used by Plymouth for its Trans-Am AAR 'Cuda, called just the "340-6" or "six barrel".
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] This race-oriented version of the already high-performance 340 featured an aluminum intake manifold mounting three Holley carburetors, a dual points ignition system, and a heavy duty short block with additional webbing to allow for aftermarket installed 4 bolt main bearing caps.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The application-specific cylinder heads featured relocated intake pushrod passages with offset rocker arms that allowed the pushrods to be moved away from the intake ports, which could improve airflow if the pushrod-clearance "hump" was ground away from the intake port by the end user.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] For the 1974 model year, it was replaced by the 360 cu in (5.9 L) engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] It was released in 1971 with a two-barrel carburetor.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 360 used the large intake port 340 heads with a smaller intake valve of 1.88 in (48 mm).
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In 1974, with the introduction of the code E58 4-barrel dual-exhaust version, at 245 hp (183 kW) SAE net, it became the most powerful LA engine with the end of 340 production.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Power started dropping from 1975 on as more emission controls were added resulting with the 1980 E58 engine only producing 185 hp (138 kW) SAE net.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Starting with 1981, the 360 was exclusively used in Dodge trucks and vans.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Some prototypes for the EH1 featured Mopar Performance W2 heads, although the production units had the standard 360 heads.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Some police package cars came from the factory with a steel crank and h-beam rods.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] There was also a "lean burn" version of the 360.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The LA360 was replaced in 1993 by the 5.9 Magnum, which shared some design parameters with the LA360, but the majority of its components were different.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Due to additional modifications, the prototype Li'l Red Express truck tested by various period magazines ran appreciably stronger than actual production examples.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The last variation of the LA series to be introduced before the Magnum upgrade was the 1988–92 throttle-body fuel injected, roller cam engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The first engines to receive these modifications were the 318 cu in (5.2 L) V8 and 239 cu in (3.9 L) V6 engines.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] A Holley/Chrysler-designed, single-point, twin-injector throttle body assembly was mounted atop a slightly redesigned cast iron intake manifold.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] An in-tank electric pump and reservoir replaced the earlier mechanical (camshaft-eccentric driven) pump.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The valvetrain was upgraded to include hydraulic roller lifters; however, cam specifications remained essentially unchanged.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The resulting engine was somewhat improved as to power and efficiency.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 5.9 L V8 engines followed suit in 1989, but also received the overall improved "308" cylinder heads (casting number 4448308) that featured significantly higher flowing exhaust ports and a return to the original 1971 (non-fast burn) combustion chamber.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] However, with other manufacturers already introducing the superior multi-point fuel injection system, Chrysler considered a more drastic upgrade program.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] As the TBI engines were being introduced, the new upgrade program was initiated in the Chrysler engineering department.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In 1992, with emissions standards becoming ever more stringent in the United States, Chrysler Corporation released the first of the upgraded engines.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In 1992, Chrysler introduced the first of a series of upgraded versions of the LA engines.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The company named their engine the "Magnum," a marketing term that had been used by the company previously to describe both the Dodge Magnum automobile and an earlier Dodge passenger car (only) engine series; the latter was based on the big-block B/RB V8 engines of the 1960s–70s.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The Chrysler Magnum engines are a series of V6, V8, and V10 powerplants used in a number of Chrysler Corporation motor vehicles, as well as in marine and industrial applications.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] This family of gasoline-burning engines lasted for over a decade, were installed in vehicles sold across the globe, and were produced in the millions.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The Magnum engine is a direct descendant of the Chrysler LA engine, which began with the 273 cu in (4.5 L) V8 in 1964.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The cylinder block remained basically the same.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] It was still a V-shaped, 90-degree design made of cast iron.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The crankshaft, located to the bottom of the block by five main bearing caps, was cast steel, and the eight connecting rods were forged steel.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The pistons were cast aluminum, with a hypereutectic design.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Cylinders were numbered from the front of the engine to the rear; cylinders 1, 3, 5, and 7 were found on the left (driver side) bank, or "bank 1," with the even numbers on the other bank.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Coolant passages were located between the cylinders.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The gerotor-type oil pump was located at the bottom-rear of the engine, and provided oil to both the crankshaft main bearings and the cylinder heads (via the lifters and pushrods, as opposed to a bored passage on LA engines).
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Chrysler's engineers also redesigned the oil seals on the crankshaft to improve anti-leak seal performance.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The oil pan was also made from thicker steel, and was installed with a more leak-resistant silicone-rubber gasket.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Gasoline was supplied to the intake manifold through a pair of steel rails that fed eight Bosch-type, top-fed, electronically actuated fuel injectors; there was one injector located in each intake runner.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Each cylinder had its own injector, thus making the fuel system a "multi-point" type.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Fuel pressure was regulated by a vacuum-controlled pressure regulator, located on the return side of the second fuel rail.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Excess fuel was thereafter delivered back to the fuel tank.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] To support the new fuel system, the intake manifold was of a new design.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Known colloquially as the "beer keg" or "kegger" manifold, the part was shaped like half of a beer barrel lying longitudinally atop the center of the V-shaped engine block.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The intake runners, which supplied the fuel and air to each cylinder, fed each of the intake ports in the newly designed cylinder heads.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The bolts that secured the intake manifold to the cylinder heads were installed at a different angle from those on the older LA engine; they threaded in vertically, rather than at the 45-degree angle of the 1966 and up LA.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Air was provided from the air filter intake to the intake manifold by a Holley-designed, aluminum, twin-venturi, mechanically actuated throttle body, which was bolted atop the intake manifold.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Each venturi was progressively bored and had a diameter of 50mm.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] To this unit were mounted the Throttle Position Sensor (TPS), Manifold Absolute Pressure (MAP) sensor and Idle Air Control (IAC) valve (initially referred to as the "AIS Motor").
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] A steel cable connected the accelerator pedal inside the vehicle to a mechanical linkage at the side of the throttle body, which acted to open the air intake butterfly valves inside the venturis.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] During idle these butterfly valves were closed, so a bypass port and the IAC valve were used to control the intake of air.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The cylinder heads were another fundamental change of the Magnum engine, being designed to meet stricter requirements in both power and emissions by increasing efficiency.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] These heads were cast iron units with new wedge-shaped combustion chambers and high-swirl valve shrouding.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Combustion chamber design was most important in these new heads: LA engine cylinder heads were given a full-relief open-chamber design, but the Magnum was engineered with a double-quench closed-chamber type.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The higher-flowing intake ports stepped up intake flow dramatically in comparison to the original LA heads, and the exhaust ports improved cylinder evacuation as well.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The shape and porting of the chambers allowed for more complete atomization of the air/fuel mixture, as well as contributing to more complete combustion; these virtues allowed for much greater efficiency of the engine as a whole.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The intake and exhaust valves were located at the top of each combustion chamber.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The valves themselves had shorter, 5/16" diameter stems, to allow for the more aggressive camshaft.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Intake valves had a port diameter of 1.92", while exhaust valves were 1.600", with 60cc combustion chambers.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Spark plugs were located at the peak of the combustion chambers' wedge, between the exhaust ports; press-in heat shields protected them from the heat of the exhaust manifolds.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Cast iron exhaust manifolds, less restrictive than units found on previous engines, were bolted to the outboard side of each head.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The new cylinder heads also featured stud-mounted rocker arms, a change from the shaft-mounted LA arms.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] This last change was due to the different oiling system of the new engine, as described in the next paragraph.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The valve covers on the Magnum have 10 bolts rather than the previous 5, for improved oil sealing.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In addition, the valve covers were made of thicker steel than earlier parts, and were installed with a silicone gasket.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The valvetrain was also updated, although it was still based on a single, center-block located camshaft pushing on hydraulic lifters and pushrods, one for each rocker arm.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] However, the cast nodular iron camshaft was of the "roller" type, with each lobe acting upon a hydraulic lifter with a roller bearing on the bottom; this made for a quieter, cooler-running valvetrain, but also allowed for a more aggressive valve lift.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Each of the lifters acted upon a steel pushrod, which were of the "oil-through" type.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Because the new pushrods also served to provide oil to the top of the cylinder head, the rockers were changed to the AMC-style, screw-mounted, bridged half-shaft type.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The new rockers also had a higher ratio: 1.6:1 compared to 1.5:1 in the LA engine, which increased leverage on the valves.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In addition, the oil boss located at the end of the cylinder head on the LA engine was left undrilled, as it was no longer needed.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] However, the boss itself was left in place, perhaps to cut down on casting and machining costs, and to allow the use of earlier LA heads.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Engine timing was controlled by the all-steel, silent Morse timing chain (some early production engines had double-row roller timing sets), which was located beneath the aluminum timing cover at the front of the engine block.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The timing chain sprockets, one each for the camshaft and crankshaft, were all-steel; for the last few years, the LA engine came with nylon teeth on the sprockets.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] At the rear of the camshaft was cut a set of helical gear teeth, these being used to spin the distributor.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Mounted to the front of the timing cover was a redesigned, counterclockwise rotation water pump, with much improved flow.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Externally, the accessory drive belt was changed to a serpentine system; coupled with an automatic belt tensioner this increased belt life, reduced maintenance and contributed to lower noise and vibration levels.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The ignition system was also all-new for the Magnum.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Controlled by a new micro-processor-equipped Single-Board Engine Controller (SBEC, also known as the ECM, or Engine Control Module), the ignition system included a distributor mounted at the rear of the engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] A 36,000-volt ignition coil, usually located at the front right of the engine, provided electrical power to the center of the distributor cap, where a spinning rotor directed the power to each of the individual cylinders' spark plug wires.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Ignition dwell, advance and retardation were electronically controlled by the SBEC.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The SBEC controlled the ignition, as well as the opening and closing of the fuel injectors.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] During cold startup, wide-open throttle and deceleration, it did this based on "open-loop," pre-programmed operating parameters.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] During normal idle and cruising, it began "closed-loop" operation, during which the module acted based upon inputs from a variety of sensors.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The basic sensors that provided input to the SBEC included the Oxygen sensor (O2), Manifold Absolute Pressure (MAP) sensor, Throttle Position Sensor (TPS), Intake Air Temperature (IAT) sensor and Coolant Temperature sensor (CTS).
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The basic actuators controlled by the SBEC's outputs included the fuel injectors, ignition coil and pickup, and the Idle Air Control (IAC) valve.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The latter controlled idle characteristics.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] However, the SBEC also controlled the operation of the charging system, air conditioning system, cruise control and, in some vehicles, transmission shifting.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] By centralizing control of these systems, the operation of the vehicle was simplified and streamlined.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Emissions output was controlled by several systems.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The EGR, or Exhaust Gas Recirculation system, brought exhaust gas from the exhaust stream up to the intake manifold, lowering peak combustion temperatures, the goal being the reduction of NOX emissions.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] A PCV, or Positive Crankcase Ventilation system, introduced oil vapor and unburnt fuel vapors from the crankcase to the intake, allowing the engine to re-use these as well.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Furthermore, gasoline vapors that would normally be released into the atmosphere were captured by the EVAP system, to then be introduced into the engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In 1996, the OBD-II on-board diagnostics system was introduced on all passenger vehicles in the United States, as per United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) regulation.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] As such, a new engine control computer was developed for vehicles powered by Magnum engines, known as the JTEC.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The new Powertrain Control Module was more complex and more intelligent, and added programming meant it could also control automatic transmission and other powertrain functions; its firmware could also be reprogrammed ("reflashed") via the same OBD-II port.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] With the introduction of the JTEC, the EGR system was dropped from Magnum engines.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] As the 5.2 L V8 was introduced in 1992, the often-forgotten V6 version of the Magnum engine became available in the Ram pickup and the more compact Dodge Dakota.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Based on the LA-series 239 cu in (3.9 L) V6, the 3.9 L Magnum featured the same changes and upgrades as the other Magnum engines.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 3.9 L is essentially a 5.2 L V8 with two cylinders removed.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Power increased substantially to 180 hp (134 kW) at 4,400 rpm and from 195 to 220 lb⋅ft (264 to 298 N⋅m) at 3,200 rpm, as compared with the previous TBI engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] For 1994, horsepower was reduced to 175 hp (130 kW), mostly because of the installation of smaller-volume exhaust manifolds; torque ratings remained the same.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] For 1997, the 3.9 L engine's torque output was increased to 225 lb⋅ft (305 N⋅m), with a compression ratio of 9.1:1.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] This engine was last produced for the 2003 Dodge Dakota pickup.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Starting in the 2004 model year, it was entirely withdrawn from production and replaced with the 3.7L PowerTech V6 engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 5.2 L Magnum, released in 1992, was an evolutionary development of the 318 cu in (5.2 L) LA engine with the same displacement.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 5.2 L was the first of the Magnum upgraded engines, followed in 1993 by the 5.9 L V8 and the 3.9 L V6.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] At the time of its introduction, the 5.2 L Magnum created 230 hp (172 kW) at 4,100 rpm and 295 lb⋅ft (400 N⋅m) at 3,000 rpm.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Production of this engine lasted until 2003, when it was completely replaced by the newer 4.7 L PowerTech SOHC V8 engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] In 1993, Chrysler Corporation released the next member of the Magnum family: the 5.9 L V8.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] This was based on the LA-series 360 cu in (5.9 L) engine, and included the same upgrades and design features as the 5.2 L.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The standard 5.9 L produced 230 hp (172 kW) at 4,000 rpm and 325 lb⋅ft (441 N⋅m) at 3,200 rpm; torque was increased to 330 lb⋅ft (447 N⋅m) at 2,800 rpm in the heavy-duty version.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 5.9 L came factory-installed in 1998–2001 Dodge Dakota R/T pickups and 2000–2003 Dodge Durango R/T SUVs.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] It was also installed in the Jeep Grand Cherokee Limited 5.9, only available in 1998.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The 5.9 L Magnum was available until the 2003 model year, when it was replaced with the 5.7 L Hemi V8 engine.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Although the pre-Magnum (1971–92) and Magnum versions of the 360 cu in (5.9 L) are both externally balanced, the two are balanced differently (the Magnum version uses lighter pistons) and each requires a uniquely balanced damper, flywheel, drive plate, or torque converter.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Bore and stroke size was 4 in × 3.58 in (101.6 mm × 90.9 mm); compression ratio was 9.1:1.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The Magnum V10 was a 488 cu in (8.0 L) V10 engine designed for use in Dodge Ram 2500 and 3500 trucks, which made its debut in 1994 and was produced through 2003.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Although Chrysler had already introduced an aluminum block Lamborghini-influenced V10 in the 1991 Dodge Viper, this engine's roots trace to the genesis of the 5.2 L Magnum V8 in 1988.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Valve covers were die-cast magnesium (AZ91D alloy), rather than stamped steel; this lowered noise levels and made for better gasket sealing.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] The Magnum V10 first became available in the 1994 model year Dodge Ram 2500 and 3500 (above 8,500 pounds GVWR), and was the most powerful gasoline-burning engine then available in any truck of that class.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Chrysler has offered a line of crate engines based on the Magnum designed to bolt into older muscle cars and street rods with little modification.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Some of the changes to facilitate this were using a 1970–93 coolant pump so that older pulleys and brackets could be used, as well as an intake manifold that uses a carburetor instead of electronic fuel injection.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] With a high lift cam and single plane intake, the crate Magnum 360 cu in (5.9 L) was rated at 380 hp (283 kW) with the Magnum heads.
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] Later models equipped with "R/T" or aluminum cylinder heads produced 390 hp (291 kW).
[src:carter-carburetor/chrysler-la-engine] A 425 hp (317 kW) bolt-in fuel injection conversion kit has also been available.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] A **geographic coordinate system** (**GCS**) is a spherical or geodetic coordinate system for measuring and communicating positions directly on Earth as latitude and longitude.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] It is the simplest, oldest, and most widely used type of the various spatial reference systems that are in use, and forms the basis for most others.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Although latitude and longitude form a coordinate tuple like a Cartesian coordinate system, geographic coordinate systems are not Cartesian because the measurements are angles and are not on a planar surface.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] A full GCS specification, such as those listed in the EPSG and ISO 19111 standards, also includes a choice of geodetic datum (including an Earth ellipsoid), as different datums will yield different latitude and longitude values for the same location.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The invention of a geographic coordinate system is generally credited to Eratosthenes of Cyrene, who composed his now-lost *Geography* at the Library of Alexandria in the 3rd century BC.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] A century later, Hipparchus of Nicaea improved on this system by determining latitude from stellar measurements rather than solar altitude and determining longitude by timings of lunar eclipses, rather than dead reckoning.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy credited him with the full adoption of longitude and latitude, rather than measuring latitude in terms of the length of the midsummer day.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy's 2nd-century *Geography* used the same prime meridian but measured latitude from the Equator instead.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] After their work was translated into Arabic in the 9th century, Al-Khwārizmī's *Book of the Description of the Earth* corrected Marinus' and Ptolemy's errors regarding the length of the Mediterranean Sea, causing medieval Arabic cartography to use a prime meridian around 10° east of Ptolemy's line.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Mathematical cartography resumed in Europe following Maximus Planudes' recovery of Ptolemy's text a little before 1300; the text was translated into Latin at Florence by Jacopo d'Angelo around 1407.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] In 1884, the United States hosted the International Meridian Conference, attended by representatives from twenty-five nations.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Twenty-two of them agreed to adopt the longitude of the Royal Observatory in Greenwich, England as the zero-reference line.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The Dominican Republic voted against the motion, while France and Brazil abstained.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] France adopted Greenwich Mean Time in place of local determinations by the Paris Observatory in 1911.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The *latitude* φ of a point on Earth's surface is defined in one of three ways, depending on the type of coordinate system.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] In each case, the latitude is the angle formed by the plane of the equator and a line formed by the point on the surface and a second point on equatorial plane.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The path that joins all points of the same latitude traces a circle on the surface of Earth, as viewed from above the north or south pole, called parallels, as they are parallel to the equator and to each other.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The north pole is 90° N; the south pole is 90° S.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The 0° parallel of latitude is defined to be the equator, the fundamental plane of a geographic coordinate system.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The equator divides the globe into Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The *longitude* λ of a point on Earth's surface is the angle east or west of a reference meridian to another meridian that passes through that point.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] All meridians are halves of great ellipses, which converge at the North and South Poles.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The meridian of the British Royal Observatory in Greenwich, in southeast London, England, is the international prime meridian, although some organizations—such as the French Institut national de l'information géographique et forestière—continue to use other meridians for internal purposes.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The antipodal meridian of Greenwich is both 180°W and 180°E.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] This is not to be conflated with the International Date Line, which partly overlaps with the 180° meridian but diverges from it in several places for political and convenience reasons, including between far eastern Russia and the far western Aleutian Islands.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The combination of these two components specifies the position of any location on the surface of Earth, without consideration of altitude or depth.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The visual grid on a map formed by lines of latitude and longitude is known as a *graticule*.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The origin/zero point of this system is located in the Gulf of Guinea about 625 km (390 mi) south of Tema, Ghana, a location often facetiously called Null Island.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] In order to use the theoretical definitions of latitude, longitude, and height to precisely measure actual locations on the physical earth, a *geodetic datum* must be used.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] A *horizonal datum* is used to precisely measure latitude and longitude, while a *vertical datum* is used to measure elevation or altitude.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Both types of datum bind a mathematical model of the shape of the earth (usually a reference ellipsoid for a horizontal datum, and a more precise geoid for a vertical datum) to the earth.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Traditionally, this binding was created by a network of control points, surveyed locations at which monuments are installed, and were only accurate for a region of the surface of the Earth.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Newer datums are based on a global network for satellite measurements (GNSS, VLBI, SLR and DORIS).
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] This combination of a mathematical model and physical binding ensures that users of the same datum obtain identical coordinates for a given physical point.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] However, different datums typically produce different coordinates for the same location (sometimes deviating several hundred meters) not due to actual movement, but because the reference system itself is shifted.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Because any spatial reference system or map projection is ultimately calculated from latitude and longitude, it is crucial that they clearly state the datum on which they are based.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] For example, a UTM coordinate based on a WGS84 realisation will be different than a UTM coordinate based on NAD27 for the same location.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Transforming coordinates from one datum to another requires a datum transformation method such as a Helmert transformation, although in certain situations a simple translation may be sufficient.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums may be global, meaning that they represent the whole Earth, or they may be regional, meaning that they represent an ellipsoid best-fit to only a portion of the Earth.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums with a regional fit of the ellipsoid that are chosen by a national cartographical organization include the North American Datums, the European ED50, and the British OSGB36.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Given a location, the datum provides the latitude $\phi$ and longitude $\lambda$ .
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] In the United Kingdom there are three common latitude, longitude, and height systems in use.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] WGS 84 differs at Greenwich from the one used on published maps OSGB36 by approximately 112 m.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Points on the Earth's surface move relative to each other due to continental plate motion, subsidence, and diurnal Earth tidal movement caused by the Moon and the Sun.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] This daily movement can be as much as a meter.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Continental movement can be up to 10 cm a year, or 10 m in a century.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] A weather system high-pressure area can cause a sinking of 5 mm.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Scandinavia is rising by 1 cm a year as a result of the melting of the ice sheets of the last ice age, but neighboring Scotland is rising by only 0.2 cm.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] These changes are insignificant if a regional datum is used, but are statistically significant if a global datum is used.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] On the GRS 80 or WGS 84 spheroid at sea level at the Equator, one latitudinal second measures 30.715 m, one latitudinal minute is 1843 m and one latitudinal degree is 110.6 km.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The circles of longitude, meridians, meet at the geographical poles, with the west–east width of a second naturally decreasing as latitude increases.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] On the Equator at sea level, one longitudinal second measures 30.92 m, a longitudinal minute is 1855 m and a longitudinal degree is 111.3 km.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The returned measure of meters per degree latitude varies continuously with latitude.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] The formulae both return units of meters per degree.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] ( $\textstyle {\beta }\,\!$ is known as the reduced (or parametric) latitude).
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Aside from rounding, this is the exact distance along a parallel of latitude; getting the distance along the shortest route will be more work, but those two distances are always within 0.6 m of each other if the two points are one degree of longitude apart.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] Like any series of multiple-digit numbers, latitude-longitude pairs can be challenging to communicate and remember.
[src:carter-carburetor/geographic-coordinate-system] These are not distinct coordinate systems, only alternative methods for expressing latitude and longitude measurements.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] A **holding company** is a company whose primary business is holding a controlling interest in the securities of other companies.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] A holding company usually does not produce goods or services itself.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] Its purpose is to own stock of other companies to create a corporate group.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] Holding companies also conduct trade and other business activities themselves.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] Holding companies reduce risk for the shareholders, and can permit the ownership and control of a number of different companies.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] They can be subsidiaries in a tiered structure.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] Holding companies are also created to hold assets such as intellectual property or trade secrets that are protected from the operating company.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] That creates a smaller risk when it comes to litigation.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] In the United States, 80% of stock, in voting and value, must be owned before tax consolidation benefits such as tax-free dividends can be claimed.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] That is, if Company A owns 80% or more of the stock of Company B, Company A will not pay taxes on dividends paid by Company B to its stockholders, as the payment of dividends from B to A is essentially transferring cash within a single enterprise.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] Any other shareholders of Company B will pay the usual taxes on dividends, as they are legitimate and ordinary dividends to these shareholders.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] In some jurisdictions around the world, holding companies are called **parent companies**.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] *The New York Times* uses the term *parent holding company*.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] Sometimes, a company intended to be a pure holding company identifies itself as such by adding "Holding" or "Holdings" to its name.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] Once a full takeover or purchase is enacted, the held company is seen to have ceased to operate as an independent entity but to have become a tending subsidiary of the purchasing company, which, in turn, becomes the parent company of the subsidiary.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] In the United Kingdom, the term *holding company* is defined by the Companies Act 2006 at section 1159.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] After the 2008 financial crisis, many U.S. investment banks converted to holding companies.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] According to the Federal Financial Institutions Examination Council's website, JPMorgan Chase, Bank of America, Citigroup, Wells Fargo, and Goldman Sachs were the five largest bank holding companies in the finance sector, as of December 2013, based on total assets.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] The Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935 caused many energy companies to divest their subsidiary businesses.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] Between 1938 and 1958 the number of holding companies declined from 216 to 18.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] An energy law passed in 2005 removed the 1935 requirements, and has led to mergers and holding company formation among power marketing and power brokering companies.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] This is sometimes done on a per-market basis.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] For example, in Atlanta both WNNX and later WWWQ are licensed to "WNNX LiCo, Inc." (LiCo meaning "license company"), both owned by Susquehanna Radio (which was later sold to Cumulus Media).
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] In determining caps to prevent excessive concentration of media ownership, all of these are attributed to the parent company, as are leased stations, as a matter of broadcast regulation.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] In the United States, a personal holding company is defined in section 542 of the Internal Revenue Code.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] A **parent company** is a company that owns enough voting power in another firm (or *subsidiary*) to control management and operations by influencing or electing its board of directors.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] The definition of a parent company differs from jurisdiction to jurisdiction, with the definition normally being defined by way of laws dealing with companies in that jurisdiction.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] When an existing company establishes a new company and keeps majority shares with itself, and invites other companies to buy minority shares, it is called a parent company.
[src:carter-carburetor/parent-company] A parent company could simply be a company that wholly owns another company, which is then known as a "wholly owned subsidiary".
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The manufacture of PCBs has declined drastically since the 1960s when problems were identified.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] With the discovery of PCBs' environmental toxicity, and classification as persistent organic pollutants, their production was banned for most uses by United States federal law on January 1, 1978.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] However, because of their longevity and widespread use as a coolant in electric transformers, PCBs still persist in built environments.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has classified PCBs as definite carcinogens in humans.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), PCBs cause cancer in animals and are probable human carcinogens.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Some PCBs share a structural similarity and toxic mode of action with dioxins.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Other toxic effects such as endocrine disruption (notably blocking of thyroid system functioning) and neurotoxicity are known.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The bromine analogues of PCBs are polybrominated biphenyls (PBBs), which have similar applications and environmental concerns.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] An estimated 1.2 million tons have been produced globally.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Though the US EPA enforced the federal ban as of 1978, PCBs continued to create health problems in later years through their continued presence in soil and sediment, and from products which were made before the ban.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 1988, Japanese scientists Tanabe et al. estimated 370,000 tons were in the environment globally, and 780,000 tons were present in products, landfills and dumps, or kept in storage.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The compounds are pale-yellow viscous liquids.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] They are hydrophobic, with low water solubilities: 0.0027–0.42 ng/L for Aroclors brand, but they have high solubilities in most organic solvents, oils, and fats.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] They have low vapor pressures at room temperature.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] They have dielectric constants of 2.5–2.7, very high thermal conductivity, and high flash points (from 170 to 380 °C).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Other physical and chemical properties vary widely across the class.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] As the degree of chlorination increases, melting point and lipophilicity increase, and vapour pressure and water solubility decrease.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs do not easily break down or degrade, which made them attractive for industries.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCB mixtures are resistant to acids, bases, oxidation, hydrolysis, and temperature change.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] They can generate extremely toxic dibenzodioxins and dibenzofurans through partial oxidation.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Intentional degradation as a treatment of unwanted PCBs generally requires high heat or catalysis (see Methods of destruction below).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs readily penetrate skin, PVC (polyvinyl chloride), and latex (natural rubber).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCB-resistant materials include Viton, polyethylene, polyvinyl acetate (PVA), polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE), butyl rubber, nitrile rubber, and Neoprene.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs are derived from biphenyl, which has the formula C12H10, sometimes written (C6H5)2.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In PCBs, some of the hydrogen atoms in biphenyl are replaced by chlorine atoms.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] There are 209 different chemical compounds in which one to ten chlorine atoms can replace hydrogen atoms.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs are typically used as mixtures of compounds and are given the single identifying CAS number 1336-36-3 .
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] About 130 different individual PCBs are found in commercial PCB products.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Toxic effects vary depending on the specific PCB.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In terms of their structure and toxicity, PCBs fall into two distinct categories, referred to as coplanar or non-*ortho*-substituted arene substitution patterns and noncoplanar or *ortho*-substituted congeners.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The coplanar group members have a fairly rigid structure, with their two phenyl rings in the same plane.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] is often used interchangeably when the environmental and toxic impact of these compounds is considered.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] positions can cause neurotoxic and immunotoxic effects, but only at concentrations much higher than those normally associated with dioxins.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] However, as they are typically found at much higher levels in biological and environmental samples they also pose health concerns, particularly to developing animals (including humans).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] As they do not activate the AhR, they are not considered part of the dioxin group.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Because of their lower overt toxicity, they have typically been of lesser concern to regulatory bodies.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Di-*ortho*-substituted, non-coplanar PCBs interfere with intracellular signal transduction dependent on calcium which may lead to neurotoxicity.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] *ortho*-PCBs can disrupt thyroid hormone transport by binding to transthyretin.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The only North American producer, Monsanto Company, marketed PCBs under the trade name **Aroclor** from 1930 to 1977.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] These were sold under trade names followed by a four-digit number.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In general, the first two digits refer to the product series as designated by Monsanto (e.g., 1200 or 1100 series); the second two numbers indicate the percentage of chlorine by mass in the mixture.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Thus, Aroclor 1260 is a 1200 series product and contains 60% chlorine by mass.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] It is a myth that the first two digits referred to the number of carbon atoms; the number of carbon atoms do not change in PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The 1100 series was a crude PCB material which was distilled to create the 1200 series PCB product.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The exception to the naming system is Aroclor 1016 which was produced by distilling 1242 to remove the highly chlorinated congeners to make a more biodegradable product.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] "1016" was given to this product during Monsanto's research stage for tracking purposes but the name stuck after it was commercialized.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Different Aroclors were used at different times and for different applications.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In electrical equipment manufacturing in the US, Aroclor 1260 and Aroclor 1254 were the main mixtures used before 1950; Aroclor 1242 was the main mixture used in the 1950s and 1960s until it was phased out in 1971 and replaced by Aroclor 1016.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] One estimate (2006) suggested that 1 million tonnes of PCBs had been produced.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] 40% of this material was thought to remain in use.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Another estimate put the total global production of PCBs on the order of 1.5 million tonnes.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The United States was the single largest producer with over 600,000 tonnes produced between 1930 and 1977.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The European region follows with nearly 450,000 tonnes through 1984.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] It is unlikely that a full inventory of global PCB production will ever be accurately tallied, as there were factories in Poland, East Germany, and Austria that produced unknown amounts of PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] As of 2002, there were still 21,500 tons of PCBs stored in the easternmost regions of Slovakia.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Although deliberate production of PCBs is banned by international treaty, significant amounts of PCBs are still being "inadvertently" produced.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Research suggests that 45,000 tons of 'by-product' PCBs are legally produced per year in the US as part of certain chemical and product formulations.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Commercial production of PCBs was banned in the United States in 1979, with the passage of the Toxic Substances Control Act (TSCA).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The utility of PCBs is based largely on their chemical stability, including low flammability and high dielectric constant.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In an electric arc, PCBs generate incombustible gases.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Use of PCBs is commonly divided into closed and open applications.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Examples of closed applications include coolants and insulating fluids (transformer oil) for transformers and capacitors, such as those used in old fluorescent light ballasts, and hydraulic fluids considered a semi-closed application.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In contrast, the major open application of PCBs was in carbonless copy ("NCR") paper, which even presently results in paper contamination.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] It was also used as a plasticizer in paints and especially "coal tars" that were used widely to coat water tanks, bridges and other infrastructure pieces.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Modern sources include pigments, which may be used in inks for paper or plastic products.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs are also still found in old equipment like capacitors, ballasts, X-ray machines, and other e-waste.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs have entered the environment through both use and disposal.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The environmental fate of PCBs is complex and global in scale.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Because of their low vapour pressure, PCBs accumulate primarily in the hydrosphere, despite their hydrophobicity, in the organic fraction of soil, and in organisms including the human body.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The immense volume of water in the oceans is still capable of dissolving a significant quantity of PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] As the pressure of ocean water increases with depth, PCBs become heavier than water and sink to the deepest ocean trenches where they are concentrated.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] A small volume of PCBs has been detected throughout the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The atmosphere serves as the primary route for global transport of PCBs, particularly for those congeners with one to four chlorine atoms.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In the atmosphere, PCBs may be degraded by hydroxyl radicals, or directly by photolysis of carbon–chlorine bonds (even if this is a less important process).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Atmospheric concentrations of PCBs tend to be lowest in rural areas, where they are typically in the picogram per cubic meter range, higher in suburban and urban areas, and highest in city centres, where they can reach 1 ng/m3 or more.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In Milwaukee, an atmospheric concentration of 1.9 ng/m3 has been measured, and this source alone was estimated to account for 120 kg/year of PCBs entering Lake Michigan.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 2008, concentrations as high as 35 ng/m3, 10 times higher than the EPA guideline limit of 3.4 ng/m3, have been documented inside some houses in the U.S.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Volatilization of PCBs in soil was thought to be the primary source of PCBs in the atmosphere, but research suggests ventilation of PCB-contaminated indoor air from buildings is the primary source of PCB contamination in the atmosphere.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In bacteria, PCBs may be dechlorinated through reductive dechlorination, or oxidized by dioxygenase enzyme.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In eukaryotes, PCBs may be oxidized by the cytochrome P450 enzyme.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Like many lipophilic toxins, PCBs undergo biomagnification and bioaccumulation primarily due to the fact that they are easily retained within organisms.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Plastic pollution, specifically microplastics, are a major contributor of PCBs into the biosphere and especially into marine environments.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs concentrate in marine environments because freshwater systems, like rivers, act as a bridge for plastic pollution to be transported from terrestrial environments into marine environments.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] It has been estimated that 88–95% of marine plastic is exported into the ocean by just 10 major rivers.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] An organism can accumulate PCBs by consuming other organisms that have previously ingested PCBs from terrestrial, freshwater, or marine environments.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The concentration of PCBs within an organism will increase over their lifetime; this process is called bioaccumulation.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCB concentrations within an organism also change depending upon which trophic level they occupy.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] When an organism occupies a high trophic level, like orcas or humans, they will accumulate more PCBs than an organism that occupies a low trophic level, like phytoplankton.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] If enough organisms with a trophic level are killed due to the accumulation of toxins, like PCB, a trophic cascade can occur.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs can cause harm to human health or even death when eaten.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs can be transported by birds from aquatic sources onto land via feces and carcasses.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs undergo xenobiotic biotransformation, a mechanism used to make lipophilic toxins more polar and more easily excreted from the body.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The biotransformation is dependent on the number of chlorine atoms present, along with their position on the rings.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Phase I reactions occur by adding an oxygen to either of the benzene rings by Cytochrome P450.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The type of P450 present also determines where the oxygen will be added; phenobarbital (PB)-induced P450s catalyze oxygenation to the meta-para positions of PCBs while 3-methylcholanthrene (3MC)-induced P450s add oxygens to the *ortho*–*meta* positions.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs containing *ortho*–*meta* and *meta*–*para* protons can be metabolized by either enzyme, making them the most likely to leave the organism.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] However, some metabolites of PCBs containing *ortho*–*meta* protons have increased steric hindrance from the oxygen, causing increased stability and an increased chance of accumulation.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Metabolism is also dependent on the species of organism; different organisms have slightly different P450 enzymes that metabolize certain PCBs better than others.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Looking at the PCB metabolism in the liver of four sea turtle species (green, olive ridley, loggerhead and hawksbill), green and hawksbill sea turtles have noticeably higher hydroxylation rates of PCB 52 than olive ridley or loggerhead sea turtles.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] This is because the green and hawksbill sea turtles have higher P450 2-like protein expression.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] This protein adds three hydroxyl groups to PCB 52, making it more polar and water-soluble.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] P450 3-like protein expression that is thought to be linked to PCB 77 metabolism, something that was not measured in this study.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Temperature plays a key role in the ecology, physiology and metabolism of aquatic species.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The rate of PCB metabolism was temperature dependent in yellow perch (*Perca flavescens*).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In fall and winter, only 11 out of 72 introduced PCB congeners were excreted and had halflives of more than 1,000 days.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] During spring and summer when the average daily water temperature was above 20 °C, persistent PCBs had halflives of 67 days.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The main excretion processes were fecal egestion, growth dilution and loss across respiratory surfaces.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The excretion rate of PCBs matched with the perch's natural bioenergetics, where most of their consumption, respiration and growth rates occur during the late spring and summer.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Since the perch is performing more functions in the warmer months, it naturally has a faster metabolism and has less PCB accumulation.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] However, multiple cold-water periods mixed with toxic PCBs with coplanar chlorine molecules can be detrimental to perch health.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Enantiomers of chiral compounds have similar chemical and physical properties, but can be metabolized by the body differently.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] This was looked at in bowhead whales (*Balaena mysticetus*) for two main reasons: they are large animals with slow metabolisms (meaning PCBs will accumulate in fatty tissue) and few studies have measured chiral PCBs in cetaceans.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] They found that the average PCB concentrations in the blubber were approximately four times higher than the liver; however, this result is most likely age- and sex-dependent.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] As reproductively active females transferred PCBs and other poisonous substances to the fetus, the PCB concentrations in the blubber were significantly lower than males of the same body length (less than 13 meters).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The toxicity of PCBs varies considerably among congeners.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The coplanar PCBs, known as nonortho PCBs because they are not substituted at the ring positions *ortho* to (next to) the other ring, (such as PCBs 77, 126 and 169), tend to have dioxin-like properties, and generally are among the most toxic congeners.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Because PCBs are almost invariably found in complex mixtures, the concept of toxic equivalency factors (TEFs) has been developed to facilitate risk assessment and regulation, where more toxic PCB congeners are assigned higher TEF values on a scale from 0 to 1.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] One of the most toxic compounds known, 2,3,7,8-tetrachlorodibenzo[p]dioxin, a PCDD, is assigned a TEF of 1.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In June 2020, State Impact of Pennsylvania stated that "In 1979, the EPA banned the use of PCBs, but they still exist in some products produced before 1979.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] They persist in the environment because they bind to sediments and soils.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In general, people are exposed to PCBs overwhelmingly through food, much less so by breathing contaminated air, and least by skin contact.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Once exposed, some PCBs may change to other chemicals inside the body.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] These chemicals or unchanged PCBs can be excreted in feces or may remain in a person's body for years, with half lives estimated at 10–15 years.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs biomagnify up the food web and are present in fish and overflow of contaminated aquifers.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Human infants are exposed to PCBs through breast milk or by intrauterine exposure through transplacental transfer of PCBs and are at the top of the food chain.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Workers recycling old equipment in the electronics recycling industry can also be exposed to PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The most commonly observed health effects in people exposed to extremely high levels of PCBs are skin conditions, such as chloracne and rashes, but these were known to be symptoms of acute systemic poisoning dating back to 1922.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Studies in workers exposed to PCBs have shown changes in blood and urine that may indicate liver damage.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In Japan in 1968, 280 kg of PCB-contaminated rice bran oil was used as chicken feed, resulting in a mass poisoning, known as Yushō disease, in over 1800 people.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Common symptoms included dermal and ocular lesions, irregular menstrual cycles and lowered immune responses.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Other symptoms included fatigue, headaches, coughs, and unusual skin sores.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Additionally, in children, there were reports of poor cognitive development.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Women exposed to PCBs before or during pregnancy can give birth to children with lowered cognitive ability, compromised immune systems, and motor control problems.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] There is evidence that crash dieters that have been exposed to PCBs have an elevated risk of health complications.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Stored PCBs in the adipose tissue become mobilized into the blood when individuals begin to crash diet.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs have shown toxic and mutagenic effects by interfering with hormones in the body.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs, depending on the specific congener, have been shown to both inhibit and imitate estradiol, the main sex hormone in females.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Imitation of the estrogen compound can feed estrogen-dependent breast cancer cells, and possibly cause other cancers, such as uterine or cervical.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Inhibition of estradiol can lead to serious developmental problems for both males and females, including sexual, skeletal, and mental development issues.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In a cross-sectional study, PCBs were found to be negatively associated with testosterone levels in adolescent boys.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] High PCB levels in adults have been shown to result in reduced levels of the thyroid hormone triiodothyronine, which affects almost every physiological process in the body, including growth and development, metabolism, body temperature, and heart rate.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] It also resulted in reduced immunity and increased thyroid disorders.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Animals that eat PCB-contaminated food, even for short periods of time, suffer liver damage and may die.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 1968 in Japan, 400,000 birds died after eating poultry feed that was contaminated with PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Animals that ingest smaller amounts of PCBs in food over several weeks or months develop various health effects, including anemia; acne-like skin conditions (chloracne); liver, stomach, and thyroid gland injuries (including hepatocarcinoma), and thymocyte apoptosis.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Other effects of PCBs in animals include changes in the immune system, behavioral alterations, and impaired reproduction.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs that have dioxin-like activity are known to cause a variety of teratogenic effects in animals.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Exposure to PCBs causes hearing loss and symptoms similar to hypothyroidism in rats.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 2013, the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) classified dioxin-like PCBs as human carcinogens.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] EPA, PCBs have been shown to cause cancer in animals and evidence supports a cancer-causing effect in humans.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Per the EPA, studies have found increases in malignant melanoma and rare liver cancers in PCB workers.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 2013, the IARC determined that the evidence for PCBs causing non-Hodgkin lymphoma is "limited" and "not consistent".
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In contrast an association between elevated blood levels of PCBs and non-Hodgkin lymphoma had been previously accepted.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In the early 1990s, Monsanto faced several lawsuits over harm caused by PCBs from workers at companies such as Westinghouse that bought PCBs from Monsanto and used them to build electrical equipment.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Monsanto and its customers, such as Westinghouse and GE, also faced litigation from third parties, such as workers at scrap yards that bought used electrical equipment and broke them down to reclaim valuable metals.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Monsanto settled some of these cases and won the others, on the grounds that it had clearly told its customers that PCBs were dangerous chemicals and that protective procedures needed to be implemented.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 2003, Monsanto and Solutia Inc., a Monsanto corporate spin-off, reached a $700 million settlement with the residents of West Anniston, Alabama, who had been affected by the manufacturing and dumping of PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 2014, the Los Angeles Superior Court found that Monsanto was not liable for cancers claimed to be from PCBs permeating the food supply of three plaintiffs who had developed non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] After a four-week trial, the jury found that Monsanto's production and sale of PCBs between 1935 and 1977 were not substantial causes of the cancer.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 2015, the cities of Spokane, San Diego, and San Jose initiated lawsuits against Monsanto to recover cleanup costs for PCB contaminated sites, alleging that Monsanto continued to sell PCBs without adequate warnings after they knew of their toxicity.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Monsanto issued a media statement concerning the San Diego case, claiming that improper use or disposal by third-parties, of a lawfully sold product, was not the company's responsibility.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In July 2015, a St Louis county court in Missouri found that Monsanto, Solutia, Pharmacia and Pfizer were not liable for a series of deaths and injuries caused by PCBs manufactured by Monsanto Chemical Company until 1977.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The trial took nearly a month and the jury took a day of deliberations to return a verdict against the plaintiffs from throughout the USA.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] "The evidence simply doesn't support the assertion that the historic use of PCB products was the cause of the plaintiffs' harms.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] We are confident that the jury will conclude, as two other juries have found in similar cases, that the former Monsanto Company is not responsible for the alleged injuries," a Monsanto statement said.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In May 2016, a Missouri state jury ordered Monsanto to pay $46.5 million to three plaintiffs whose exposure to PCB caused non-Hodgkin lymphoma.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In December 2016, the state of Washington filed suit in King County.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The state sought damages and clean up costs related to PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In March 2018 Ohio Attorney General Mike DeWine also filed a lawsuit against Monsanto over health issues posed by PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] On November 21, 2019, a federal judge denied a bid by Monsanto to dismiss a lawsuit filed by LA County calling the company to clean up cancer-causing PCBs from Los Angeles County waterways and storm sewer pipelines.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The lawsuit calls for Monsanto to pay for cleanup of PCBs from dozens of waterways, including the LA River, San Gabriel River and the Dominguez Watershed.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In June 2020, Bayer agreed to pay $650 million to settle local lawsuits related to Monsanto's pollution of public waters in various areas of the United States with PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In that same month of June 2020, Attorney General Bob Ferguson announced Monsanto will pay 95 million dollar settlement after the 3 year litigation.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] This litigation began related to the costs of water contamination.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCB contamination is found in 13 bodies of water, where fish advisory warnings have been given from the PCBs that have accumulated in the tissues.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Some of the consequences, include affecting other aspects of the ecosystem, such as contamination on bays, soil and other related species like birds and other animal life.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 2023, over 90 Vermont school districts joined a lawsuit against Monsanto alleging that PCBs created by the company were used in the construction of their schools.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The Vermont Attorney General's office also filed its own lawsuit against Monsanto related to the use of its PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] A settlement between Monsanto and students, parents and staff of Monroe school occurred in August 2025.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The legal campaign started in 2018, where the plaintiffs alleged Monsanto knew about the toxicity of PCBs that were used in the school infrastructure.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Not only did the school not remove the banned material to ensure safety of students, but Monsanto themselves knew of the health implications of PCBs before they were banned.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Further controversy occurred because evidence obtained by the Washington state who is in an ongoing legal battle with Monsanto shows that they knew of the risks of PCBs before the 1979 ban, based on over 20,000 internal documents.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In October 2025, NC state university filed a lawsuit against Monsanto over PCBs used in construction of Poe Hall on campus in 1971.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health is currently evaluating the health hazards.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 1865, the first "PCB-like" chemical was discovered, and was found to be a byproduct of coal tar.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Years later in 1876, German chemist Oscar Döbner (Doebner) synthesized the first PCB in a laboratory.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Since then, large amounts of PCBs were released into the environment, to the extent that there are even measurable amounts of PCBs in feathers of birds currently held in museums before the production of PCBs peaked.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 1935, Monsanto Chemical Company (later Solutia Inc) took over commercial production of PCBs from Swann Chemical Company which had begun in 1929.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs, originally termed "chlorinated diphenyls", were commercially produced as mixtures of isomers at different degrees of chlorination.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The electric industry used PCBs as a non-flammable replacement for mineral oil to cool and insulate industrial transformers and capacitors.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] PCBs were also commonly used as heat stabilizer in cables and electronic components to enhance the heat and fire resistance of PVC.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In the 1930s, the toxicity associated with PCBs and other chlorinated hydrocarbons, including polychlorinated naphthalenes, was recognized because of a variety of industrial incidents.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Between 1936 and 1937, there were several medical cases and papers released on the possible link between PCBs and its detrimental health effects.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Public health Service official described the wife and child of a worker from the Monsanto Industrial Chemical Company who exhibited blackheads and pustules on their skin.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The official attributed these symptoms to contact with the worker's clothing after he returned from work.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 1937, a conference about the hazards was organized at Harvard School of Public Health, and a number of publications referring to the toxicity of various chlorinated hydrocarbons were published before 1940.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 1947, Robert Brown reminded chemists that Arochlors were "objectionably toxic": "Thus the maximum permissible concentration for an 8-hr. day is 1 mg. per cu.m. [1.0 mg/m3] of air.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] They also produce a serious and disfiguring dermatitis".
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] (Kaneka Corporation) first produced PCBs, and continued until 1972.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Through the 1960s Monsanto Chemical Company knew increasingly more about PCBs' harmful effects on humans and the environment, per internal leaked documents released in 2002, yet PCB manufacture and use continued with few restraints until the 1970s.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 1966, PCBs were determined by Swedish chemist Sören Jensen to be an environmental contaminant.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Jensen, according to a 1994 article in *Sierra*, named chemicals PCBs, which previously, had simply been called "phenols" or referred to by various trade names, such as Aroclor, Kanechlor, Pyrenol, Chlorinol and others.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 1972, PCB production plants existed in Austria, West Germany, France, the UK, Italy, Japan, Spain, the USSR and the US.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Stone of the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation (NYSDEC) first published his findings that PCBs were leaking from transformers and had contaminated the soil at the bottom of utility poles.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] There have been allegations that Industrial Bio-Test Laboratories engaged in data falsification in testing relating to PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] In 2003, Monsanto and Solutia Inc., a Monsanto corporate spinoff, reached a US$700 million settlement with the residents of West Anniston, Alabama, who had been affected by the manufacturing and dumping of PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Existing products containing PCBs which are "totally enclosed uses" such as insulating fluids in transformers and capacitors, vacuum pump fluids, and hydraulic fluid, are allowed to remain in use in the US.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] The public, legal, and scientific concerns about PCBs arose from research indicating they are likely carcinogens having the potential to adversely impact the environment and, therefore, undesirable as commercial products.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p01] Despite active research spanning five decades, extensive regulatory actions, and an effective ban on their production since the 1970s, PCBs still persist in the environment and remain a focus of attention.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1999, the Dioxin Affair occurred when 50 kg of PCB transformer oils were added to a stock of recycled fat used for the production of 500 tonnes of animal feed, eventually affecting around 2,500 farms in several countries.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The name *Dioxin Affair* was coined from early misdiagnosis of dioxins as the primary contaminants, when in fact they turned out to be a relatively small part of the contamination caused by thermal reactions of PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The PCB congener pattern suggested the contamination was from a mixture of Aroclor 1260 and 1254.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Over 9 million chickens, and 60,000 pigs were destroyed because of the contamination.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The extent of human health effects has been debated, in part because of the use of differing risk assessment methods.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] One group predicted increased cancer rates, and increased rates of neurological problems in those exposed as neonates.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] A second study suggested carcinogenic effects were unlikely and that the primary risk would be associated with developmental effects due to exposure in pregnancy and neonates.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Two businessmen who knowingly sold the contaminated feed ingredient received two-year suspended sentences for their role in the crisis.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The Italian company Caffaro, located in Brescia, specialized in producing PCBs from 1938 to 1984, following the acquisition of the exclusive rights to use the patent in Italy from Monsanto.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The pollution resulting from this factory and the case of Anniston, in the US, are the largest known cases in the world of PCB contamination in water and soil, in terms of the amount of toxic substance dispersed, size of the area contaminated, number of people involved and duration of production.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The values reported by the local health authority (ASL) of Brescia since 1999 are 5,000 times above the limits set by Ministerial Decree 471/1999 (levels for residential areas, 0.001 mg/kg).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] As a result of this and other investigations, in June 2001, a complaint of an environmental disaster was presented to the Public Prosecutor's Office of Brescia.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Research on the adult population of Brescia showed that residents of some urban areas, former workers of the plant, and consumers of contaminated food, have PCB levels in their bodies that are in many cases 10–20 times higher than reference values in comparable general populations.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] PCBs entered the human food supply by animals grazing on contaminated pastures near the factory, especially in local veal mostly eaten by farmers' families.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The exposed population showed an elevated risk of Non-Hodgkin lymphoma, but not for other specific cancers.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1968, a mixture of dioxins and PCBs got into rice bran oil produced in northern Kyushu.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Contaminated cooking oil sickened more than 1,860 people.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In Okinawa, high levels of PCB contamination in soil on Kadena Air Base were reported in 1987 at thousands of parts per million, some of the highest levels found in any pollution site in the world.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In December 2008, a number of Irish news sources reported testing had revealed "extremely high" levels of dioxins, by toxic equivalent, in pork products, ranging from 80 to 200 times the EU's upper safe limit of 1.5 pg WHO-TEQDFP/μg i.e.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Brendan Smith, the Minister for Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, stated the pork contamination was caused by PCB-contaminated feed that was used on 9 of Ireland's 400 pig farms, and only one feed supplier was involved.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Smith added that 38 beef farms also used the same contaminated feed, but those farms were quickly isolated and no contaminated beef entered the food chain.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] While the contamination was limited to just 9 pig farms, the Irish government requested the immediate withdrawal and disposal of all pork-containing products produced in Ireland and purchased since September 1, 2008.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] This request for withdrawal of pork products was confirmed in a press release by the Food Safety Authority of Ireland on December 6.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] It is thought that the incident resulted from the contamination of fuel oil used in a drying burner at a single feed processor, with PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The resulting combustion produced a highly toxic mixture of PCBs, dioxins and furans, which was included in the feed produced and subsequently fed to a large number of pigs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In Kenya, a number of cases have been reported in the 2010s of thieves selling transformer oil, stolen from electric transformers, to the operators of roadside food stalls for use in deep frying.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] When used for frying, it is reported that transformer oil lasts much longer than regular cooking oil.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The downside of this misuse of the transformer oil is the threat to the health of the consumers, due to the presence of PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The chemical plant Chemko in Strážske (east Slovakia) was an important producer of polychlorinated biphenyls for the former communist bloc (Comecon) until 1984.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Chemko contaminated a large part of east Slovakia, especially the sediments of the Laborec river and reservoir Zemplínska šírava.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Between 1962 and 1983, the Iskra Kondenzatorji company in Semič (White Carniola, Southeast Slovenia) manufactured capacitors using PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Due to the wastewater and improperly disposed waste products, the area (including the Krupa and Lahinja rivers) became highly contaminated with PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The pollution was discovered in 1983, when the Krupa river was meant to become a water supply source.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The area was sanitized then, but the soil and water are still highly polluted.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Traces of PCBs were found in food (eggs, cow milk, walnuts) and Krupa is still the most PCB-polluted river in the world.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Several cetacean species have very high mean blubber PCB concentrations likely to cause population declines and suppress population recovery.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Striped dolphins, bottlenose dolphins and orcas were found to have mean levels that markedly exceeded all known marine mammal PCB toxicity thresholds.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The western Mediterranean Sea and the south-west Iberian Peninsula were identified as "hotspots".
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Monsanto manufactured PCBs at its chemical plant in Newport, South Wales, until the mid- to late-1970s.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] During this period, waste matter, including PCBs, from the Newport site was dumped at a disused quarry near Groes-faen, west of Cardiff, and Penhros landfill site from where it continues to be released in waste water discharges.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Monsanto was the only company that manufactured PCBs in the US.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Its production was entirely halted in 1977.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Olguin rejected a proposed $650 million settlement from Bayer, the company which acquired Monsanto in 2018, and allowed Monsanto-related lawsuits involving PCB to proceed.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] PCBs originating from Monsanto Chemical Company in Anniston, Alabama, were dumped into Snow Creek, which then spread to Choccolocco Creek, then Logan Martin Lake.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In the early 2000s, class action lawsuits were settled by local land owners, including those on Logan Martin Lake, and Lay Reservoir (downstream on the Coosa River), for the PCB pollution.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Donald Stewart, former Senator from Alabama, first learned of the concerns of hundreds of west Anniston residents after representing a church which had been approached about selling its property by Monsanto.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Stewart went on to be the pioneer and lead attorney in the first and majority of cases against Monsanto and focused on residents in the immediate area known to be most polluted.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Other attorneys later joined in to file suits for those outside the main immediate area around the plant; one of these was the late Johnnie Cochran.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 2007, the highest pollution levels remained concentrated in Snow and Choccolocco Creeks.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Concentrations in fish have declined and continue to decline over time; sediment disturbance, however, can resuspend the PCBs from the sediment back into the water column and food web.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] San Francisco Bay has been contaminated by PCBs, "a legacy of PCBs spread widely across the land surface of the watershed, mixed deep into the sediment of the Bay, and contaminating the Bay food web".
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Levels of PCBs in fish and shellfish exceed thresholds for safe consumption.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Signs around the Bay warn anglers of which species to avoid.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] State water quality regulators set a Total Maximum Daily Load for PCBs require city and county governments around the Bay to implement control measures to limit PCBs in urban runoff.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] An important part of the second, revised version of this permit was the requirement for municipalities to install green infrastructure with a goal of reducing pollutant levels in stormwater.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In New Haven, the decommissioned English Station has a high concentration of PCB contamination due to the chemicals used in the running of the plant.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] This, along with asbestos contamination, has made cleaning and demolishing the abandoned site extremely difficult.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The PCB contamination has spread to the soil, and to the river, where locals will sometimes fish unaware of the danger.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1976, environmentalists found PCBs in the sludge at Waukegan Harbor, the southwest end of Lake Michigan.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] They were able to trace the source of the PCBs back to the Outboard Marine Corporation that was producing boat motors next to the harbor.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] By 1982, the Outboard Marine Corporation was court-ordered to release quantitative data referring to their PCB waste released.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The data stated that from 1954 they released 100,000 tons of PCB into the environment, and that the sludge contained PCBs in concentrations as high as 50%.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1989, during construction near the Zilwaukee bridge, workers uncovered an uncharted landfill containing PCB-contaminated waste which cost $100,000 to clean up.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Much of the Great Lakes area were still heavily polluted with PCBs in 1988, despite extensive remediation work.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] From the late 1950s through 1977, Westinghouse Electric used PCBs in the manufacture of capacitors in its Bloomington, Indiana, plant.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Reject capacitors were hauled and dumped in area salvage yards and landfills, including Bennett's Dump, Neal's Landfill and Lemon Lane Landfill.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Workers also dumped PCB oil down factory drains, which contaminated the city sewage treatment plant.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The City of Bloomington gave away the sludge to area farmers and gardeners, creating anywhere from 200 to 2,000 sites, which remain unaddressed.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Over 1,000 tons of PCBs were estimated to have been dumped in Monroe and Owen counties.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Although federal and state authorities have been working on the sites' environmental remediation, many areas remain contaminated.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Concerns have been raised regarding the removal of PCBs from the karst limestone topography, and regarding the possible disposal options.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] To date, the Westinghouse Bloomington PCB Superfund site case does not have a Remedial Investigation/Feasibility Study (RI/FS) and Record of Decision (ROD), although Westinghouse signed a US Department of Justice Consent Decree in 1985.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The 1985 consent decree required Westinghouse to construct an incinerator that would incinerate PCB-contaminated materials.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Because of public opposition to the incinerator, however, the State of Indiana passed a number of laws that delayed and blocked its construction.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The parties to the consent decree began to explore alternative remedies in 1994 for six of the main PCB contaminated sites in the consent decree.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Hundreds of sites remain unaddressed as of 2014.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Monroe County will never be PCB-free, as noted in a 2014 Indiana University program about the local contamination.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] On February 15, 2008, Monroe County approved a plan to clean up the three remaining contaminated sites in the City of Bloomington, at a cost of $9.6 million to CBS Corp., the successor of Westinghouse.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1999, Viacom bought CBS, so they are current responsible party for the PCB sites.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Pittsfield, in western Massachusetts, was home to the General Electric (GE) transformer, capacitor, and electrical generating equipment divisions.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The electrical generating division built and repaired equipment that was used to power the electrical utility grid throughout the nation.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] PCB-contaminated oil routinely migrated from GE's 254-acre (1.03 km2) industrial plant located in the very center of the city to the surrounding groundwater, nearby Silver Lake, and to the Housatonic River, which flows through Massachusetts, Connecticut, and down to Long Island Sound.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] PCB-containing solid material was widely used as fill, including oxbows of the Housatonic River.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Fish and waterfowl which live in and around the river contain significant levels of PCBs and are not safe to eat.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] EPA designated the Pittsfield plant and several miles of the river as a Superfund site in 1997, and ordered GE to remediate the site.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] EPA and GE began a cleanup of the area in 1999.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] New Bedford Harbor, which is a listed Superfund site, contained some of the highest sediment concentrations of PCBs in the marine environment.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Cleanup of the area began in 1994 and is mostly complete as of 2020.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Investigations into historic waste dumping in the Bliss Corner neighborhood have revealed the existence of PCBs, among other hazardous materials, buried in soil and waste material.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Rose Chemical Inc. began processing and disposing of materials contaminated with PCBs in Holden, Missouri, a small rural community about 40 miles (64 km) east of Kansas City.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] From 1982 until 1986, nearly 750 companies, including General Motors Corp., Commonwealth Edison, Illinois Power Co. and West Texas Utilities, sent millions of pounds of PCB contaminated materials to Holden for disposal.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Instead, according to prosecutors, the company began storing the contaminated materials while falsifying its reports to the EPA to show they had been removed.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] After investigators learned of the deception, Rose Chemical was closed and filed for bankruptcy.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The site had become the nation's largest waste site for the chemical PCB.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In the four years the company was operational, the EPA inspected it four times and assessed $206,000 in fines but managed to collect only $50,000.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] After the plant closed the state environmental agency found PCB contamination in streams near the plant and in the city's sewage treatment sludge.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] A 100,000 square-foot warehouse and unknown amounts of contaminated soil and water around the site had to be cleaned up.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Most of the surface debris, including close to 13 million pounds of contaminated equipment, carcasses and tanks of contaminated oil, had to be removed.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Carolan, owner of Rose Chemical, and five others pleaded guilty in 1989 to committing fraud or falsifying documents.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Carolan and two other executives served sentences of less than 18 months; the others received fines and were placed on probation.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Cleanup costs at the site are estimated at $35 million.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Two launch facilities at Malmstrom Air Force Base showed PCB levels higher than the thresholds recommended by the Environmental Protection Agency when extensive sampling began of active U.S. intercontinental ballistic missile bases to address specific cancer concerns in 2023.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Pollution of the Hudson River is largely due to dumping of PCBs by General Electric from 1947 to 1977.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] GE dumped an estimated 1.3 million pounds of PCBs into the Hudson River during these years.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The PCBs came from the company's two capacitor manufacturing plants at Hudson Falls and Fort Edward, New York.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] This pollution caused a range of harmful effects to wildlife and people who eat fish from the river or drink the water.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1984, EPA declared a 200-mile (320 km) stretch of the river, from Hudson Falls to New York City, to be a Superfund site requiring cleanup.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Extensive remediation actions on the river began in the 1970s with the implementation of wastewater discharge permits and consequent control or reduction of wastewater discharges, and sediment removal operations, which have continued into the 21st century.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Love Canal is a neighborhood in Niagara Falls, New York, that was heavily contaminated with toxic waste including PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Eighteen Mile Creek in Lockport, New York, is an EPA Superfund site for PCBs contamination.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] PCB pollution at the State Office Building in Binghamton was responsible for what is now considered to be the first indoor environmental disaster in the United States.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1981, a transformer explosion in the basement spewed PCBs throughout the entire 18-story building.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The contamination was so severe that cleanup efforts kept the building closed for 13 years.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The crime, known as "the midnight dumpings", occurred over nearly two weeks, as drivers of a black-painted tanker truck drove down one side of rural Piedmont highways spraying PCB-laden waste and then up the other side the following night.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Hunt, Jr., state officials then erected large, yellow warning signs along the contaminated highways that read: "CAUTION: PCB Chemical Spills Along Highway Shoulders".
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The illegal dumping is believed to have been motivated by the passing of the Toxic Substances Control Act (TSCA), which became effective on August 2, 1978, and increased the expense of chemical waste disposal.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Within a couple of weeks of the crime, Robert Burns and his sons, Timothy and Randall, were arrested for dumping the PCBs along the roadsides.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Burns was a business partner of Robert "Buck" Ward Jr., of the Ward PCB Transformer Company, in Raleigh.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Burns and sons pleaded guilty to state and Federal criminal charges; Burns received a three to five-year prison sentence.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Ward was acquitted of state charges in the dumping, but was sentenced to 18 months prison time for violation of TSCA.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Cleanup and disposal of the roadside PCBs generated controversy, as the Governor's plan to pick up the roadside PCBs and to bury them in a landfill in rural Warren County were strongly opposed in 1982 by local residents.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In October 2013, at the request of the South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control (SCDHEC), the City of Charlotte, North Carolina, decided to stop applying sewage sludge to land while authorities investigated the source of PCB contamination.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In February 2014, the City of Charlotte admitted PCBs have entered their sewage treatment centers as well.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] After the 2013 SCDHEC had issued emergency regulations, the City of Charlotte discovered high levels of PCBs entering its sewage waste water treatment plants, where sewage is converted to sewage sludge.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The city at first denied it had a problem, then admitted an "event" occurred in February 2014, and in April that the problem had occurred much earlier.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The city stated that its very first test with a newly changed test method revealed very high PCB levels in its sewage sludge farm field fertilizer.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Because of the widespread use of the contaminated sludge, SCDHEC subsequently issued PCB fish advisories for nearly all streams and rivers bordering farm fields that had been applied with city waste.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The Clyde cancer cluster (also known as the Sandusky County cancer cluster) is a childhood cancer cluster that has affected many families in Clyde, Ohio, and surrounding areas.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] PCBs were found in soil in a public park within the area of the cancer cluster.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In Akron, Ohio, soil was contaminated and noxious PCB-laden fumes had been put into the air by an electrical transformer deconstruction operation from the 1930s to the 1960s.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] From 1955 until 1977, the Sangamo Weston plant in Pickens, South Carolina, used PCBs to manufacture capacitors, and dumped 400,000 pounds of PCB contaminated wastewater into the Twelve Mile Creek.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1990, the EPA declared the 228 acres (0.92 km2) site of the capacitor plant, its landfills and the polluted watershed, which stretches nearly 1,000 acres (4.0 km2) downstream to Lake Hartwell as a Superfund site.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Two dams on the Twelve Mile Creek are to be removed and on Feb.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] 22, 2011 the first of two dams began to be dismantled.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Some contaminated sediment is being removed from the site and hauled away, while other sediment is pumped into a series of settling ponds.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 2013, the state environmental regulators issued a rare emergency order, banning all sewage sludge from being land applied or deposited on landfills, as it contained very high levels of PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The problem had not been discovered until thousands of acres of farm land in the state had been contaminated by the hazardous sludge.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] A criminal investigation to determine the perpetrator of this crime was launched.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] As of 2015, several bodies of water in the state of Washington were contaminated with PCBs, including the Columbia River, the Duwamish River, Green Lake, Lake Washington, the Okanogan River, Puget Sound, the Spokane River, the Walla Walla River, the Wenatchee River, and the Yakima River.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] A study by Washington State published in 2011 found that the two largest sources of PCB flow into the Spokane River were City of Spokane stormwater (44%) and municipal and industrial discharges (20%).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] PCBs entered the environment through paint, hydraulic fluids, sealants, inks and have been found in river sediment and wildlife.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Spokane utilities will spend $300 million to prevent PCBs from entering the river in anticipation of a 2017 federal deadline to do so.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In August 2015 Spokane joined other U.S. cities like San Diego and San Jose, California, and Westport, Massachusetts, in seeking damages from Monsanto.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] From 1954 until 1971, the Fox River in Appleton, Wisconsin, had PCBs deposited into it from Appleton Paper/NCR, P.H.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Gladfelter, Georgia-Pacific and other notable local paper manufacturing facilities.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The Wisconsin DNR estimates that after wastewater treatment the PCB discharges to the Fox River due to production losses ranged from 81,000 kg to 138,000 kg.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The production of Carbon Copy Paper and its byproducts led to the discharge into the river.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Polychlorinated biphenyls have been discovered in organisms living in the Mariana Trench in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Levels were as high as 1,900 nanograms per gram of amphipod tissue in the organisms analyzed.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1972 the Japanese government banned the production, use, and import of PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1973, the use of PCBs in "open" or "dissipative" sources (such as plasticisers in paints and cements, casting agents, fire retardant fabric treatments and heat stabilizing additives for PVC electrical insulation, adhesives, paints and waterproofing, railroad ties) was banned in Sweden.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1981, the UK banned closed uses of PCBs in new equipment, and nearly all UK PCB synthesis ceased; closed uses in existing equipment containing in excess of 5 litres of PCBs were not stopped until December 2000.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 1976, concern over the toxicity and persistence (chemical stability) of PCBs in the environment led the United States Congress to ban their domestic production, effective January 1, 1978, pursuant to the Toxic Substances Control Act.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] To implement the law, EPA banned new manufacturing of PCBs, but issued regulations that allowed for their continued use in electrical equipment for economic reasons.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] EPA began issuing regulations for PCB usage and disposal in 1979.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The agency has issued guidance publications for safe removal and disposal of PCBs from existing equipment.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] EPA defined the "maximum contaminant level goal" for public water systems as zero, but because of the limitations of water treatment technologies, a level of 0.5 parts per billion is the actual regulated level (maximum contaminant level).
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] PCBs were technically attractive because of their inertness, which includes their resistance to combustion.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Nonetheless, they can be effectively destroyed by incineration at 1000 °C.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] When combusted at lower temperatures, they convert in part to more hazardous unintentional persistent organic pollutants, including polychlorinated dibenzofurans and dibenzo-p-dioxins.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] When conducted properly, the combustion products are water, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen chloride.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In some cases, the PCBs are combusted as a solution in kerosene.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] PCBs have also been destroyed by pyrolysis in the presence of alkali metal carbonates.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Thermal desorption is highly effective at removing PCBs from soil.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] PCBs are fairly chemically unreactive; they resist oxidation and hydrolysis commonly encountered in industrial applications, alongside high thermal stability and electrical resistivity, low water solubility and flammability, and resistance to acids and bases.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] These properties make it attractive for its use in industry.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Many chemical compounds are available to destroy or reduce the PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Commonly, PCBs are degraded by basic mixtures of glycols, which displace some or all chloride.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Also effective are reductants such as sodium or sodium naphthalene.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The use of microorganisms to degrade PCBs from contaminated sites, relying on multiple microorganisms' co-metabolism, is known as bioremediation of polychlorinated biphenyl.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Some micro-organisms degrade PCBs by reducing the C-Cl bonds.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Microbial dechlorination tends to be rather slow-acting in comparison to other methods.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Enzymes extracted from microbes can show PCB activity.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] In 2005, *Shewanella oneidensis* biodegraded a high percentage of PCBs in soil samples.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] A low voltage current can stimulate the microbial degradation of PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] There is research showing that some ligninolytic fungi can degrade PCBs.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The remediation, or removal, of PCBs from estuarian and coastal river sediments is quite difficult due to the overlying water column and the potential for resuspension of contaminants during the removal process.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] The most common method of PCB extraction from sediments is to dredge an area and dispose of the sediments in a landfill.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] This method is troubling for a number of reasons, namely that it has a risk of resuspension of the chemicals as the sediments are disturbed, and this method can be very damaging to ecosystems.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] A potential cost effective, low risk remediation technique is bioremediation.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Bioremediation involves the use of biota to remediate sediments.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Phytoremediation, the use of plants to remediate soils, has been found to be effective for a broad range of contaminants such as mercury, PCB, and PAHs in terrestrial soils.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] A promising study conducted in New Bedford Harbor found that *Ulva rigida*, a type of seaweed common throughout the world, is effective at removing PCB from sediments.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] During a typical bloom in New Bedford Harbor, *U. rigida* forms a thick mat that lies on top of and in contact with the sediment.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] This allows for *U. rigida* to uptake large amounts of PCB from the sediment with concentrations of PCB in *U. rigida* reaching 1580 μg kg−1 within 24 hours of the bloom.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Live tissue tended to take up higher concentrations of PCB than dead tissue, but this is not to say that dead tissue did not still take up large amounts of PCB as well.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] For a complete list of the 209 PCB congeners, see PCB congener list.
[src:carter-carburetor/polychlorinated-biphenyl-p02] Note that biphenyl, while not technically a PCB congener because of its lack of chlorine substituents, is still typically included in the literature.
